<TITLE> EU congratulates Russia's Medvedev, stresses values </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 BRUSSELS, March 3 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - The European Commission congratulated Dmitry Medvedev as Russia's new leader, avoiding direct criticism of the way his election was handled but stressing the importance of Russia following democratic values. "I am confident that under president Medvedev the Russian Federation and the European Union will consolidate and develop their strategic partnership," Commission President Jose Manuel Barroso said on Monday. The partnership should be based "not only on common interests but also on respect for the values to which we both declared our commitment," he said in a statement. Medvedev has pledged to continue the policies of outgoing President Vladimir Putin, his mentor. Relations between the EU and Moscow have at times been uneasy with many European politicians expressing concern over what they called the increasingly autocratic policies of Russia's leadership. Many have expressed concern about the curbs Russia imposed on international observers of the election. Asked by a reporter why Barroso was congratulating Medvedev amid criticism of the way the ballot had been conducted, a Commission spokeswoman said Brussels had previously expressed concern about the absence of proper monitoring. She dismissed media suggestions that the EU might need to take tougher action. "In our view dialogue is always better than shutting the door," the spokeswoman said, adding the bloc wanted to engage even more intensely with Russia on issues such as media freedom, democracy and freedom of assembly. Diplomats say the EU is treading carefully over the handling of Russia's election to avoid antagonising its large neighbour, which is a key energy supplier. Russia's state-controlled gas giant Gazprom still headed by Medvedev, cut supplies to Ukraine by a quarter of its needs over a debt row. The Commission said Gazprom had told Brussels that gas supplies to the EU would not be affected by the Russian gas export monopoly's row with Ukrai
